packages/publish/README.md:150:Koota supports relations between entities using the `relation` function. Relations allow you to build graphs by creating connections between entities with efficient queries.
packages/publish/README.md:181:Relations can contain data like any trait.
packages/publish/README.md:201:Relations can automatically destroy related entities when their counterpart is destroyed using the `autoDestroy` option.
packages/publish/README.md:300:Relations can be queried with specific targets and wildcard targets using `*`.
packages/publish/README.md:344:#### Tracking relation changes
packages/publish/README.md:346:Relations work with tracking modifiers to detect when entities gain, lose, or update relations. Changes can only be tracked on relations that have a store.
packages/publish/README.md:349:> You can currently only track changes to all relations of a given type, such as `ChildOf`, but not specific relation pairs, such as `ChildOf(parent)`.
packages/publish/README.md:379:#### Relation events
packages/publish/README.md:381:Relations emit events per **pair**. This makes it easy to know exactly which target was involved.
packages/publish/README.md:383:- `onAdd(Relation, (entity, target) => {})` triggers when `entity.add(Relation(target))` is called.
packages/publish/README.md:384:- `onRemove(Relation, (entity, target) => {})` triggers when `entity.remove(Relation(target))` is called.
packages/publish/README.md:385:- `onChange(Relation, (entity, target) => {})` triggers when relation **store data** is updated with `entity.set(Relation(target), data)` (only for relations created with a `store`).
packages/publish/README.md:402:Hooks also accept **relation pairs** for target-specific filtering. `ChildOf(parent)` only fires for that specific target, while `ChildOf('*')` fires for any target (equivalent to passing the relation itself).
